The paper deals with analyzing data from location-based social networks, which falls under the category of social computing (cs.SOC). The authors use a probabilistic model to extract patterns of urban activity, which involves data mining and machine learning techniques, making it relevant to the categories of data mining (cs.SI), machine learning (cs.LG), and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also discusses similarities and differences between city regions, which could fall under the category of spatial databases (cs.DB) or possibly even software engineering (cs.SE) if the focus is on developing tools for analyzing and visualizing the data.
